article.description:
Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson each scored 18 points to lead the Houston Comets to a 73-55 victory over the
Minnesota Lynx on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Houston wins its fifth in a row, eighth in past nine
article.linkText: Swoopes, Thompson lead way as Comets continue to roll
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson each scored
18 points to lead the Houston Comets to a 73-55 victory over the
Minnesota Lynx on Tuesday night.

	   Tiffani Johnson added 13 for the Comets (10-3), who have won
five in a row and eight of their last nine. Thompson, who scored 31
points in Houston's 71-58 victory Sunday at Portland, has scored 101
points in her last six games.

	   ''I think this was Tiffani's best game,'' Comets coach Van
Chancellor said. ''But it also goes to show more than anything else
that if you can vary your approach on offense and your big players
play well, you can win a lot of games.''

	   The Comets led the entire game to improve to 12-0 overall against the Lynx.

	   Minnesota (4-8) has lost five consecutive games and Houston is the
only team Minnesota has never defeated.

	   Johnson was 6-for-10 from the field and had five rebounds to
help keep Minnesota at bay.

	   ''I know coach told me it was my best game, but I think I still
can do better,'' Johnson said. ''The big thing was that we took
control early and never let Minnesota get back in the game.''

	   The Comets, the league leader in defense at 59.3 points a game
held the Lynx to just 37.5 percent shooting from the field.
Minnesota, playing without No. 2 scorer Svetlana Abrosimova, who
sat out with a lower back strain, got few second-chance shots and
were called twice for shot-clock violations.

	   ''I thought it was a very good team effort,'' Chancellor said.
''The idea was that because Minnesota is such a young team, we
wanted to get ahead and stay ahead. There were others with more
points and rebounds, but Tiffani got some of the biggest ones.''

	   Tamara Moore scored 16 points, and Katie Smith added 12 for
Minnesota.

	   ''We tried hard, but we were off track with our confidence,''
Minnesota coach Brian Agler said. ''Fatigue might have been a
factor. We'll give them tomorrow off and see what happens.''

	   Houston hit its first five shots and jumped out to a 19-8 lead
in the first six minutes. Moore, who scored just eight points in
her first five games with the Lynx, hit a pair of 3-pointers as the
Lynx cut the deficit to 21-19. But the Comets pulled away late in
the half and led 36-26 at the break.

	   Minnesota never got closer than five points in the second half.
